<HEADLINE>
<P>
COLLEGE BASKETBALL ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
CSUN WOMEN FALL IN OPENER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Friday was a day of firsts for the Cal State Northridge women's basketball 
team. The Matadors played their first game as a Division I team and their first 
game under Coach Janet Martin. 
</P>
<P>
They also experienced their first loss at the Division I level, falling, 68-35, 
to Cal State Fullerton in the first round of the four-team Fullerton 
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
Northridge fell behind, 35-19, at halftime and struggled offensively throughout 
the evening, shooting 26% from the field. 
</P>
<P>
Northridge's Julie Arlotto finished five of 13 from the field and scored a 
team-leading 10 points. No other Northridge starter scored more than four 
points. Haily Griffith and Jody Bittner came off the bench to support Arlotto 
with six points each. 
</P>
<P>
Arlotto grabbed eight rebounds, and point guard Joan Weinerth led the team with 
10 rebounds. Fullerton led Northridge in total rebounds, 43-42. 
</P>
<P>
Fullerton center Genia Miller notched game-high totals of 24 points and 11 
rebounds. Former Golden West star Claudette Jackson had 11 points for 
Fullerton. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
In other women's games: 
</P>
<P>
Moorpark 90, Cypress 35 -- Former El Camino Real High standouts Lisa Huffaker 
and Kerrie Marshall led Moorpark in a nonconference rout at home. 
</P>
<P>
Huffaker scored a game-high 21 points and Marshall had 20 points and 10 
rebounds for Moorpark (5-1). 
</P>
<P>
Amy Chandler scored 12 points and had 10 assists and teammate Angie Long had 15 
points and a game-high 11 rebounds for Moorpark. Cypress is 1-4. 
</P>
<P>
Canyons 68, Hancock 58 -- Kim Posey came within one point of her single-game 
career high, scoring 20 points and pulling down 12 rebounds to lead the host 
Cougars in the nonconference victory. 
</P>
<P>
Canyons (3-1) was aided by Keira Irwin's 15 points and eight assists and 
Shannon Solway's 10 points. Canyons' starting center, Jennifer Haig, was 
limited to about 10 minutes because of foul trouble. 
</P>
<P>
The Cougars took a 38-25 lead in the first half before Hancock (3-1) scored 11 
unanswered points. Canyons extended a nine-point halftime lead to 17 but again 
allowed a Hancock run that cut the lead to four points with four minutes 
remaining. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
MEN 
</P>
<P>
Cal Baptist 91, Cal Lutheran 80 -- The Kingsmen could not contain Cal Baptist's 
Greg Fisher and lost the nonconference game in Thousand Oaks. 
</P>
<P>
Fisher scored a game-high 27 points, finishing the first half with 17 on 
eight-of-10 shooting from the field. 
</P>
<P>
Chris Johnson led the Kingsmen (1-2) with 22 points and Jeff deLaveaga added 21 
points and three assists. 
</P>
<P>
Joe Cohen had 13 points while Tom Sglav and Carl Champion each added 10 for Cal 
Lutheran. 
</P>
<P>
Cal Baptist (3-1) held a 39-38 lead at the half. But the Kingsmen opened the 
final period with two DeLaveaga three-point baskets and went ahead, 65-62, 
midway through the second half. Cal Baptist then scored 15 unanswered points, 
and the Kingsmen never recovered. 
</P>
<P>
Ventura 92, Harbor 75 -- Lester Neal led Ventura to a first-round victory in 
the Ventura tournament with 24 points and 14 rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
Ventura (4-1) will play Malcolm X of Chicago in the second round at 8 tonight. 
</P>
<P>
DiJon Bernard and Uba Satterfield each added 19 points for Ventura, and Jerry 
Dalton scored 11. Harbor dropped to 5-2. 
</P>
<P>
Oxnard 65, L.A. City 57 -- Oxnard scored 44 second-half points to rebound from 
a seven-point halftime deficit in the first round of the Ventura tournament. 
</P>
<P>
Oxnard's Don Mitchell scored a game-high 26 points. Freshmen Shawn Talley and 
Tim Thomas each added 11 points. 
</P>
<P>
Oxnard (5-1) will play El Camino in the second round at 6 tonight. 
</P>
<P>
L. A. City is 4-1. 
</P>
