<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Deficits Loom in 30 States: At least 30 states face budget deficits because of 
the rising cost of services, falling tax revenues and slackening consume 
spending, according to surveys by the National Assn. of State Budget Officers 
and the Boston Globe. The deficits range from $42 million in Tennessee to $1 
billion in New York. 
</P>
<P>
Consumers are spending less, and the less they spend, the more likely 
businesses are to lay off workers. State governments also have trimmed their 
payrolls. Job losses, by both public and private employers, are adding to state 
spending, as unemployed workers sign up for state benefits and more families 
join welfare rolls. Such layoffs have depressed states' third major source of 
revenue: personal income taxes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
