<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: REAL ESTATE; 
</P>
<P>
HOME BUILDERS NOW MORE CAUTIOUS THAN OPTIMISTIC ABOUT '91 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by John O'Dell, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
No kidding! 
</P>
<P>
Home builders in California have changed their attitude and now are "cautious" 
instead of "optimistic" when viewing prospects for 1991, according to the 
California Building Industry Assn. 
</P>
<P>
The trade group says it discovered this switch in a survey conducted earlier 
this month. 
</P>
<P>
The telephone survey also found that while not all areas of the state are 
hurting (the San Joaquin and Central valley markets are described as moderate 
to hot), the coastal urban markets are "most affected by the production and 
sales downturn." 
</P>
</TEXT>
